urlLink Nation Books These days, virtually everybody seems to be down on the war on drugs. Politicians and pundits at every point along the ideological spectrum, from the governors of New Mexico and Minnesota to the former mayor of Baltimore, have railed against its wastefulness. Detroit Police Chief Jerry Oliver blames it for exacerbating inner-city crime. The Economist magazine has called for an immediate halt in the "war." Rightwing icon William F. Buckley calls it a "plague that consumes an estimated $75 billion per year in public money." Christopher Hitchens has labeled it "grotesque, state-sponsored racketeering." Medical marijuana campaigns are gaining momentum nationwide.  Check out Mike Gray's recent release from NationBooks for a compelling and comprehensive survey of why the US government's anti-drug campaign has become so widely reviled.  Busted by Mike Gray